⸻

A clean control system (fits your frame)

1. Entry condition (why this lever at all?)

Use pressure/fear only if:
	•	there is immediate harm, exploitation, or boundary violation
	•	softer signals have already failed or are too slow

If not → don’t escalate

⸻

2. Bounded scope (where does it apply?)
	•	target the behavior, not the person
	•	keep it time-limited
	•	no spillover into unrelated domains

⸻

3. Exit condition (this is the critical piece)

You must define this before you engage:

“When X happens, we return to neutral.”

Examples:
	•	compliance achieved
	•	boundary respected
	•	situation stabilized

If there’s no exit → it becomes identity

⸻

4. Audit (your anti-corruption layer)

Afterward:
	•	Did it work?
	•	Did it overshoot?
	•	Did it distort perception?

If you skip this → drift is guaranteed

⸻

Reframing your “fear is kindness”

There is a version of that that holds:

“Clear consequences prevent worse outcomes.”

That’s different from:

“Fear is the tool”

It’s more precise—and safer.

